# Accessing S3 with Kui

Kui has experimental support for using standard shell commands to manipulate your S3 objects. Some of the commands also support parallel operations.

#### ** !! This support is still experimental. Please do not use Kui's S3 support against your production data. **

Kui currently supports the following S3 providers. It will attempt to discover the credentials and endpoints, and make them accessible using a given mount point:

- [minio](https://min.io/), accessible via `/s3/minio/bucket/object`
- [IBM Cloud Object Storage](https://www.ibm.com/cloud/object-storage), accessible via `/s3/ibm/bucket/object`

We are eager to add support for more S3 providers. [Let us know](https://github.com/IBM/kui/issues/new) of your requirements.

# Accessing S3 with Kui

Kui has experimental support for using standard shell commands to manipulate your S3 objects. Some of the commands also support parallel operations.

#### ** !! This support is still experimental. Please do not use Kui's S3 support against your production data. **

Kui currently supports the following S3 providers. It will attempt to discover the credentials and endpoints, and make them accessible using a given mount point:

- [minio](https://min.io/), accessible via `/s3/minio/bucket/object`
- [IBM Cloud Object Storage](https://www.ibm.com/cloud/object-storage), accessible via `/s3/ibm/bucket/object`

We are eager to add support for more S3 providers. [Let us know](https://github.com/IBM/kui/issues/new) of your requirements.

## Available Commands

The following commands support s3 filepaths. For example, when using minio, a filepath would be `/s3/minio/myBucket/myObject`.

- `cp src dst`, where either or both of the source and destination can be s3 filepaths. You may provide multiple sources, and each may be a [glob pattern](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glob_(programming)). If you add the `-P` option, the created S3 objects will have the public bit set.

- `ls f1 f2 f3`. As with `cp`, you may intermix s3 and local files, and use glob patterns.

- `rmdir`, `rm`, and `mv` are also supported

- Highly experimental: `gzip f1 f2 f3`, which will attempt to parallelize the gzip across the s3 globs you have specified. This operation currently requires a Job scheduling backend to have been identified. We cover this in more detail to the right.

## Available Commands

The following commands support s3 filepaths. For example, when using minio, a filepath would be `/s3/minio/myBucket/myObject`.

- `cp src dst`, where either or both of the source and destination can be s3 filepaths.

## Parallelizing your Tasks

If Kui detects a connection to a supported Job scheduling backend, it will attempt to parallelize certain operations against your S3 objects. The list of supported schedulers is small (one!) at the moment:

- [IBM CodeEngine](https://cloud.ibm.com/docs/codeengine?topic=codeengine-getting-started)
